778
00:51:12,170 --> 00:51:14,600
<i>But don't cash in your chips
just yet, gentlemen...</i>

779
00:51:14,600 --> 00:51:19,360
<i>... because now it's the mongoose
who holds the winning card!</i>

780
00:51:44,600 --> 00:51:46,830
Hey! Hey!

781
00:51:47,600 --> 00:51:49,710
Hey, hey, hey! What are you doing?!

782
00:51:49,710 --> 00:51:51,880
- Holy crapping hell.
- What the hell is that?

783
00:51:51,880 --> 00:51:54,280
- Stop the crane. Stop it.
- Stop the crane!

784
00:51:54,280 --> 00:51:56,320
- Hey.
- Hey, what are you doing?

785
00:51:56,450 --> 00:51:58,110
Us? What are you doing?

786
00:51:58,320 --> 00:51:59,980
I was watching TV.

787
00:52:00,180 --> 00:52:03,850
- Well, we're demolishing this place.
- Are you nuts? I live here!

788
00:52:03,850 --> 00:52:06,790
- Is that a TV?
- Yes, that's a TV! It's my TV!

789
00:52:06,790 --> 00:52:09,930
- Well, what's your TV doing in there?
- I said I live here, stupid!

790
00:52:09,930 --> 00:52:11,710
It's where I keep my stuff!

791
00:52:11,900 --> 00:52:15,190
My name's on the goddamn buzzer!
Harold Crick.

792
00:52:15,400 --> 00:52:18,370
Apartment 2-B, 1893 McCarthy!

793
00:52:19,340 --> 00:52:21,800
- Did you say 1893?
- Yes!

794
00:52:28,410 --> 00:52:30,580
I'm not exactly sure it was plot.

795
00:52:30,580 --> 00:52:33,820
I was hoping you'd say it was
just a really bad coincidence.

796
00:52:33,820 --> 00:52:37,450
Meeting an insurance agent the day
your policy runs out is coincidence.

797
00:52:37,450 --> 00:52:41,360
Getting a letter from the emperor
saying that he's visiting is plot.

798
00:52:41,360 --> 00:52:44,520
Having your apartment eaten
by a wrecking ball...

799
00:52:44,730 --> 00:52:46,580
...is something else entirely.

800
00:52:48,000 --> 00:52:51,460
Harold, you don't control your fate.

801
00:52:52,200 --> 00:52:54,640
- I know.
- You do?

802
00:52:56,210 --> 00:52:57,940
Okay. Come with me.

803
00:52:58,140 --> 00:53:01,040
Hey, Tom, can you leave that
till tomorrow?

804
00:53:01,610 --> 00:53:04,950
You were right.
This narrator might very well kill you...

805
00:53:04,950 --> 00:53:09,770
...so I humbly suggest that you just
forget all this and go live your life.

806
00:53:09,850 --> 00:53:14,800
Go live my life? I am living my life.
I'd like to continue to live my life.

807
00:53:14,860 --> 00:53:19,190
I know. Of course. I mean all of it.
However long you have left.

808
00:53:19,400 --> 00:53:23,030
You know, I mean, Howard,
you could use it to have an adventure.

809
00:53:23,030 --> 00:53:27,770
<i>You know, invent something, or just
finish reading Crime and Punishment.</i>

810
00:53:27,770 --> 00:53:32,080
Hell, Harold, you could just eat
nothing but pancakes if you wanted.

811
00:53:32,080 --> 00:53:34,070
What's wrong with you?

812
00:53:34,280 --> 00:53:37,620
Hey. I don't wanna eat
nothing but pancakes. I wanna live.

813
00:53:37,620 --> 00:53:40,820
Who in their right mind in a
choice between pancakes and living...

814
00:53:40,820 --> 00:53:41,990
...chooses pancakes?

815
00:53:41,990 --> 00:53:45,090
Harold, if you'd pause to think
I believe you'd realize...

816
00:53:45,090 --> 00:53:47,490
...that that answer's
inextricably contingent...

817
00:53:47,490 --> 00:53:49,690
...upon the type of life being led...

818
00:53:51,160 --> 00:53:54,260
...and, of course,
the quality of the pancakes.

819
00:53:56,130 --> 00:53:58,580
You don't understand
what I'm saying.

820
00:53:59,340 --> 00:54:00,360
Yes, I do.

821
00:54:01,610 --> 00:54:05,480
But you have to understand that this
isn't a philosophy or a literary theory...

822
00:54:05,480 --> 00:54:07,480
...or a story to me. It's my life.

823
00:54:07,480 --> 00:54:12,180
Absolutely. So just go make it the one
you've always wanted.

824
00:54:19,790 --> 00:54:21,830
I never expected
that they would have...

825
00:54:21,830 --> 00:54:23,860
- Do you want one, two?
- I want one.

826
00:54:23,860 --> 00:54:26,160
- One?
- I want two.

827
00:54:37,170 --> 00:54:39,110
All right, so here's your room.

828
00:54:39,110 --> 00:54:41,700
Or as I like to call it, Sleep Pod Two.

829
00:54:42,310 --> 00:54:43,610
Thanks, Dave.

830
00:54:43,810 --> 00:54:47,310
No problem, dude.
It'll be nice having you around.

831
00:54:48,350 --> 00:54:51,590
- How long you planning on staying?
- I'm not sure.

832
00:54:57,430 --> 00:55:01,920
Dave, can I pose a somewhat abstract,
purely hypothetical question?

833
00:55:02,400 --> 00:55:03,870
Sure.

834
00:55:04,570 --> 00:55:06,730
If you knew you were gonna die...

835
00:55:08,070 --> 00:55:09,900
...possibly soon...

836
00:55:10,310 --> 00:55:12,240
...what would you do?

837
00:55:14,080 --> 00:55:15,880
Wow, I don't know.

838
00:55:16,710 --> 00:55:18,880
Am I the richest man in the world?

839
00:55:18,880 --> 00:55:21,080
No, you're you.

840
00:55:22,720 --> 00:55:24,240
Do I have a superpower?

841
00:55:25,160 --> 00:55:26,450
No, you're you.

842
00:55:26,660 --> 00:55:30,460
I know I'm me,
but do I have a superpower?

843
00:55:31,260 --> 00:55:33,200
No, why would you
have a superpower?

844
00:55:33,200 --> 00:55:35,930
I don't know,
you said it was hypothetical.

845
00:55:35,930 --> 00:55:38,990
Fine. Yes. You're really good at math.

846
00:55:39,400 --> 00:55:41,710
That's not a power, that's a skill.

847
00:55:42,010 --> 00:55:44,610
Okay, you're good at math
and you're invisible.

848
00:55:44,610 --> 00:55:47,510
- And you know you're gonna die.
- Okay, okay.

849
00:55:48,180 --> 00:55:50,420
That's easy, I'd go to space camp.

850
00:55:51,120 --> 00:55:52,710
Space camp?

851
00:55:52,920 --> 00:55:57,930
Yeah, it's in Alabama. It's where kids
go to learn how to become astronauts.

852
00:55:58,620 --> 00:56:01,200
I've always wanted to go
since I was 9.

853
00:56:01,760 --> 00:56:04,660
You're invisible
and you'd go to space camp?

854
00:56:04,730 --> 00:56:07,760
I didn't pick invisible,
you picked invisible.

855
00:56:08,100 --> 00:56:10,670
Aren't you too old
to go to space camp?

856
00:56:11,340 --> 00:56:14,440
You're never too old
to go to space camp, dude.

857
00:56:45,440 --> 00:56:46,400
Space camp.

858
00:56:47,770 --> 00:56:50,540
<i>One hundred and twenty-two
guitars.</i>

859
00:56:50,540 --> 00:56:53,210
<i>Seven hundred and thirty-two
strings.</i>

860
00:56:53,210 --> 00:56:55,550
<i>Two hundred and fifty-seven
pickups.</i>

861
00:56:55,550 --> 00:56:59,180
<i>One hundred and eighty-nine
volume knobs.</i>

862
00:56:59,820 --> 00:57:05,120
<i>Here Harold stood, face to face
with his oldest desire.</i>

863
00:57:05,660 --> 00:57:08,650
<i>And stand is almost all Harold did.</i>

864
00:57:09,130 --> 00:57:12,360
<i>It wasn't just about finding
a guitar.</i>

865
00:57:12,360 --> 00:57:17,560
<i>It was about finding a guitar
that said something about Harold.</i>

866
00:57:17,770 --> 00:57:19,870
<i>Unfortunately, this guitar said:</i>

867
00:57:19,870 --> 00:57:24,820
<i>"When I get back to Georgia,
that woman gonna feel my pain. "</i>

868
00:57:25,740 --> 00:57:28,080
<i>This one said something
along the lines of:</i>

869
00:57:28,080 --> 00:57:31,050
<i>"Why, yes, these pants are Lycra. "</i>

870
00:57:31,680 --> 00:57:34,550
<i>These said, "I'm very sensitive,
very caring...</i>

871
00:57:34,550 --> 00:57:39,170
<i>... and I have absolutely no idea
how to play the guitar. "</i>

872
00:57:42,260 --> 00:57:46,220
<i>"I'm compensating for something.
Guess what. "</i>

873
00:57:50,870 --> 00:57:52,850
<i>And then Harold saw it.</i>

874
00:57:53,740 --> 00:57:57,240
<i>A damaged and terribly mistreated
sea-foam-green Fender...</i>

875
00:57:57,240 --> 00:57:59,080
<i>... staring back at him.</i>

876
00:57:59,080 --> 00:58:01,010
<i>Despite its obvious maladies...</i>

877
00:58:01,010 --> 00:58:04,480
<i>... the guitar spoke
with conviction and swagger.</i>

878
00:58:04,480 --> 00:58:09,320
<i>In fact, it looked Harold directly
in the eye and very plainly stated:</i>

879
00:58:09,320 --> 00:58:12,020
<i>"I rock. "</i>

880
00:58:12,890 --> 00:58:14,390
Just breathe. Watch it!

881
00:58:14,390 --> 00:58:18,620
We've got a 21 -year-old male
with a gunshot wound to the chest.

882
00:58:19,130 --> 00:58:20,390
There you go.

883
00:58:20,760 --> 00:58:25,200
Shot in a gang fight?
Harold's not in a gang.

884
00:58:25,740 --> 00:58:27,670
Man in tweed?

885
00:58:29,870 --> 00:58:33,210
There's nothing wrong with him,
he just likes looking at sick people.

886
00:58:33,210 --> 00:58:35,410
Oddly spoken with disdain.

887
00:58:35,680 --> 00:58:37,110
This isn't working.

888
00:58:37,310 --> 00:58:39,890
Well... I don't even know
why we're here.

889
00:58:39,950 --> 00:58:41,850
I don't think we're supposed
to be here.

890
00:58:41,850 --> 00:58:45,290
- You said I needed visual stimuli.
- I meant a museum.

891
00:58:45,290 --> 00:58:47,660
I don't need a goddamn museum.
I need the infirm.

892
00:58:47,660 --> 00:58:49,650
You are the infirm.

893
00:58:50,160 --> 00:58:52,900
You're right. The problem is
these people aren't dead...

894
00:58:52,900 --> 00:58:54,940
...they're just severely injured.

895
00:58:55,530 --> 00:58:58,500
Excuse me,
where are the dying people?

896
00:58:59,900 --> 00:59:02,740
Most of these people
are sick or injured...

897
00:59:02,940 --> 00:59:05,040
Which is great, don't get me wrong.

898
00:59:05,040 --> 00:59:07,910
- But they're gonna get better,
which doesn't really help me.

899
00:59:07,910 --> 00:59:11,450
Is there any way to see the people
who aren't going to get better?

900
00:59:11,450 --> 00:59:12,420
Excuse me?

901
00:59:12,620 --> 00:59:16,020
I'd like to see, if at all possible,
the ones who aren't gonna make it.

902
00:59:16,020 --> 00:59:17,860
You know, the dead-for-sure ones.

903
00:59:17,860 --> 00:59:20,690
I'm sorry,
are you suffering from anything?

904
00:59:23,030 --> 00:59:25,220
Just writer's block.

905
00:59:33,000 --> 00:59:35,120
<i>With every awkward strum...</i>

906
00:59:35,270 --> 00:59:38,940
<i>... Harold Crick became stronger
in who he was...</i>

907
00:59:38,940 --> 00:59:42,670
<i>... what he wanted,
and why he was alive.</i>

908
00:59:43,920 --> 00:59:46,780
<i>Harold no longer ate alone.</i>

909
00:59:47,020 --> 00:59:50,220
<i>He no longer counted brushstrokes.</i>

910
00:59:50,420 --> 00:59:53,020
<i>- Harold, I'll see you.
- He no longer wore neckties.</i>

911
00:59:53,020 --> 00:59:53,990
Bye, Dave.

912
00:59:54,260 --> 00:59:59,940
<i>And, therefore, no longer worried
about the time it took to put them on.</i>

913
01:00:01,430 --> 01:00:05,460
<i>He no longer counted his steps
to the bus stop.</i>

914
01:00:07,940 --> 01:00:13,240
<i>Instead, Harold did that
which had terrified him before.</i>

915
01:00:13,450 --> 01:00:16,820
<i>That which had eluded him
Monday through Friday...</i>

916
01:00:16,820 --> 01:00:19,980
<i>... for so many years.</i>

917
01:00:20,190 --> 01:00:22,720
<i>That which the unrelenting lyrics...</i>

918
01:00:22,720 --> 01:00:26,950
<i>... of numerous punk-rock songs
told him to do:</i>

919
01:00:27,390 --> 01:00:30,790
<i>Harold Crick lived his life.</i>

920
01:00:40,000 --> 01:00:42,800
<i>But despite resuscitating his life...</i>

921
01:00:43,010 --> 01:00:47,250
<i>... reviving his hope, and instilling
a few wicked calluses...</i>

922
01:00:47,250 --> 01:00:50,740
<i>... Harold's journey
was still incomplete.</i>

923
01:00:51,280 --> 01:00:57,220
<i>And Harold's wristwatch wasn't about
to let him miss another opportunity.</i>

924
01:01:06,030 --> 01:01:07,730
Ms Pascal?

925
01:01:07,930 --> 01:01:10,660
- Ms Pascal?
- Mr Crick.

926
01:01:11,370 --> 01:01:13,860
- Hi.
- Hi.

927
01:01:14,310 --> 01:01:16,870
- Hi.
- Hi.

928
01:01:17,080 --> 01:01:19,040
I'm glad I caught you.

929
01:01:19,880 --> 01:01:21,180
Oh, yeah? Why?

930
01:01:22,480 --> 01:01:25,850
Because I wanted
to bring these to you.

931
01:01:27,620 --> 01:01:29,810
- Really?
- Yeah.

932
01:01:30,020 --> 01:01:34,390
So you can't accept gifts,
but you can give them?

933
01:01:35,330 --> 01:01:36,630
- Listen...
- I don't know.

934
01:01:36,630 --> 01:01:39,260
That seems a little inconsistent,
doesn't it, Mr Crick?

935
01:01:39,260 --> 01:01:40,700
Very inconsistent, yes.

936
01:01:40,700 --> 01:01:43,230
I'll tell you what.
I'll purchase them.

937
01:01:43,230 --> 01:01:44,880
- No.
- No, no, no, really...

938
01:01:44,900 --> 01:01:47,680
...I'd like to purchase them.
What are they?

939
01:01:48,240 --> 01:01:49,640
Flours.

940
01:01:50,310 --> 01:01:53,740
- What?
- I brought you flours.

941
01:02:04,620 --> 01:02:08,620
And you carried them
all the way here?

942
01:02:10,260 --> 01:02:15,390
Ms Pascal, I've been odd
and I know that I've been odd.

943
01:02:16,430 --> 01:02:19,230
And I want you.

944
01:02:19,770 --> 01:02:22,240
- What?
- There's so many reasons.

945
01:02:22,440 --> 01:02:25,810
There's so many influences in my life
that are telling me...

946
01:02:25,810 --> 01:02:27,530
...at times quite literally...

947
01:02:27,580 --> 01:02:30,550
...that I should come here
and bring you these...

948
01:02:31,450 --> 01:02:34,020
...but I'm doing this
because I want you.

949
01:02:34,850 --> 01:02:36,720
You want me?

950
01:02:37,220 --> 01:02:39,750
In no uncertain terms.

951
01:02:42,560 --> 01:02:47,790
Isn't there some very clear
and established...

952
01:02:48,000 --> 01:02:51,630
...rule about fraternization?

953
01:02:51,840 --> 01:02:54,030
- Auditor-auditee protocol?
- Yeah.

