01:21:55,020 --> 01:21:56,640
Have you written it?

1195
01:21:57,180 --> 01:21:58,740
I can... No.

1196
01:21:58,950 --> 01:22:01,050
- Have you written it?
- An outline.

1197
01:22:01,050 --> 01:22:03,120
Okay. But it's just an outline, right?

1198
01:22:03,120 --> 01:22:04,910
- Yeah, sort of.
- "Sort of"?

1199
01:22:04,920 --> 01:22:06,660
- It's just not typed.
- "Not typed"?!

1200
01:22:06,660 --> 01:22:08,360
- Maybe that's okay.
- What does that mean?

1201
01:22:08,360 --> 01:22:11,970
- I'm sorry, I'm trying to write a book.
- What do you mean it's "okay"?

1202
01:22:11,970 --> 01:22:14,200
- What do you mean you're sorry?
- Kay.

1203
01:22:14,200 --> 01:22:15,960
Let him read it.

1204
01:22:18,810 --> 01:22:20,570
Let him read it.

1205
01:22:35,420 --> 01:22:37,860
- Did you find her?
- Yeah.

1206
01:22:38,320 --> 01:22:41,660
- And?
- I may already be dead...

1207
01:22:41,860 --> 01:22:43,660
...just not typed.

1208
01:22:44,700 --> 01:22:45,690
Is that it?

1209
01:22:47,730 --> 01:22:49,030
Did you read it?

1210
01:22:49,240 --> 01:22:51,530
I tried, but I couldn't.

1211
01:22:53,110 --> 01:22:55,040
You have to read it.

1212
01:22:55,580 --> 01:22:58,710
You have to tell me
what to do or what not to do.

1213
01:22:58,710 --> 01:23:01,150
If I can avoid it...

1214
01:23:02,550 --> 01:23:04,520
If I have a chance...

1215
01:23:04,950 --> 01:23:06,440
Please.

1216
01:23:13,290 --> 01:23:14,760
Okay.

1217
01:23:15,430 --> 01:23:16,620
Okay.

1218
01:23:55,500 --> 01:23:57,600
And here's your uniform.

1219
01:23:58,810 --> 01:24:02,770
It's a go. Banetta's outside,
she'll assign you your locker.

1220
01:24:03,780 --> 01:24:06,680
- And you roll.
- I'm ready.

1221
01:25:03,940 --> 01:25:05,700
Professor Hilbert?

1222
01:25:07,570 --> 01:25:09,840
- Hi, Harold.
- Hi.

1223
01:25:11,780 --> 01:25:13,110
You look tired.

1224
01:25:13,850 --> 01:25:16,140
No, no, just calm.

1225
01:25:19,590 --> 01:25:21,450
Harold, I'm sorry.

1226
01:25:25,160 --> 01:25:26,890
You have to die.

1227
01:25:27,900 --> 01:25:29,090
What?

1228
01:25:29,300 --> 01:25:31,790
It's her masterpiece.

1229
01:25:34,100 --> 01:25:39,300
It's possibly the most important novel
in her already stunning career...

1230
01:25:39,510 --> 01:25:43,170
...and it's absolutely no good
unless you die at the end.

1231
01:25:44,250 --> 01:25:46,250
I've been over it again and again...

1232
01:25:46,250 --> 01:25:49,880
...and I know how hard this is
for you to hear.

1233
01:25:53,950 --> 01:25:57,220
You're asking me
to knowingly face my death?

1234
01:25:58,330 --> 01:25:59,950
Yes.

1235
01:26:01,500 --> 01:26:03,120
Really?

1236
01:26:04,100 --> 01:26:05,400
Yes.

1237
01:26:15,110 --> 01:26:19,570
I thought you'd...
I thought you'd find something.

1238
01:26:20,710 --> 01:26:22,010
I'm sorry, Harold.

1239
01:26:24,820 --> 01:26:29,350
Can't we just try and just see
if she can change it?

1240
01:26:29,560 --> 01:26:32,020
- No.
- No?

1241
01:26:32,230 --> 01:26:33,630
Harold...

1242
01:26:34,500 --> 01:26:37,760
...in the grand scheme
it wouldn't matter.

1243
01:26:39,970 --> 01:26:42,770
- Yes, it would.
- No.

1244
01:26:44,870 --> 01:26:46,840
I could change.

1245
01:26:49,080 --> 01:26:51,200
I could quit my job.

1246
01:26:51,410 --> 01:26:54,040
I could go away with Ana.

1247
01:26:54,480 --> 01:26:57,080
I could be someone else.

1248
01:26:57,920 --> 01:27:00,010
Harold, listen to me.

1249
01:27:00,220 --> 01:27:02,620
I can't die right now.

1250
01:27:05,160 --> 01:27:07,680
It's just really bad timing.

1251
01:27:10,130 --> 01:27:13,630
No one wants to die, Harold,
but unfortunately we do.

1252
01:27:15,040 --> 01:27:16,560
Harold...

1253
01:27:17,240 --> 01:27:19,230
Harold, listen to me.

1254
01:27:21,340 --> 01:27:24,470
Harold, you will die someday,
sometime.

1255
01:27:24,680 --> 01:27:26,840
Heart failure at the bank.

1256
01:27:27,350 --> 01:27:29,540
Choke on a mint.

1257
01:27:30,480 --> 01:27:34,020
Some long, drawn-out disease
you contracted on vacation.

1258
01:27:34,020 --> 01:27:37,750
You will die. You will absolutely die.

1259
01:27:38,590 --> 01:27:42,050
Even if you avoid this death,
another will find you.

1260
01:27:42,260 --> 01:27:48,100
And I guarantee that it won't be nearly
as poetic or meaningful...

1261
01:27:48,500 --> 01:27:50,470
...as what she's written.

1262
01:27:53,810 --> 01:27:55,640
I'm sorry...

1263
01:27:56,840 --> 01:27:59,880
...but it's the nature of all tragedies,
Harold.

1264
01:28:00,550 --> 01:28:04,380
The hero dies,
but the story lives on forever.

1265
01:28:42,860 --> 01:28:47,340
- There's an empty seat right there.
- No, I wanna sit down over here.

1266
01:29:22,760 --> 01:29:24,130
Kay?

1267
01:29:35,710 --> 01:29:37,110
Kay?

1268
01:29:39,750 --> 01:29:42,580
How many people
do you think I've killed?

1269
01:29:44,650 --> 01:29:46,950
- Kay.
- How many?

1270
01:29:47,450 --> 01:29:48,910
- I don't know.
- Eight.

1271
01:29:49,590 --> 01:29:53,750
- Kay...
- I've killed eight people. I counted.

1272
01:29:54,390 --> 01:29:56,120
They're fictional. Get up.

1273
01:29:56,330 --> 01:29:58,300
Harold Crick isn't fictional.

1274
01:29:58,730 --> 01:30:01,500
- I don't...
- He isn't fictional, Penny.

1275
01:30:02,570 --> 01:30:06,790
Every book I've ever written ends
with someone dying. Every one.

1276
01:30:07,410 --> 01:30:09,810
Really nice people too.

1277
01:30:10,010 --> 01:30:13,970
The book about Helen
the schoolteacher.

1278
01:30:15,080 --> 01:30:20,250
I killed her
the day before summer vacation.

1279
01:30:21,020 --> 01:30:23,080
How cruel is that?

1280
01:30:23,560 --> 01:30:26,920
And the civil engineer, Edward.

1281
01:30:27,130 --> 01:30:28,560
The one I trapped...

1282
01:30:28,760 --> 01:30:34,290
...with a heart attack in rush hour.

1283
01:30:34,500 --> 01:30:36,330
I killed him.

1284
01:30:38,110 --> 01:30:40,130
I killed...

1285
01:30:41,210 --> 01:30:43,300
Penny, I killed them all.

1286
01:31:17,080 --> 01:31:19,480
Miss Eiffel? Miss Eiffel?

1287
01:31:20,780 --> 01:31:22,650
- Harold.
- Hi.

1288
01:31:22,920 --> 01:31:26,280
- I just finished it.
- You just...

1289
01:31:26,490 --> 01:31:29,320
Yeah, I read it all in one read
on the bus.

1290
01:31:30,190 --> 01:31:31,850
It's lovely.

1291
01:31:32,060 --> 01:31:34,300
I like the part about the guitars.

1292
01:31:35,260 --> 01:31:39,130
Well, thanks, thanks. Goo...
Well, listen, I'm...

1293
01:31:39,330 --> 01:31:43,900
No, I read it and I loved it.
And there's only one way it can end.

1294
01:31:44,710 --> 01:31:48,440
I mean, I don't have much background
in literary anything...

1295
01:31:48,440 --> 01:31:50,420
...but this seems simple enough.

1296
01:31:53,410 --> 01:31:56,820
I love your book.
And I think you should finish it.

1297
01:32:14,070 --> 01:32:16,170
<i>The night before his death...</i>

1298
01:32:16,170 --> 01:32:20,660
<i>... Harold unsuspectingly went about
some usual business.</i>

1299
01:32:21,310 --> 01:32:24,080
<i>He finished his outstanding audits.</i>

1300
01:32:25,710 --> 01:32:28,450
<i>He made a few phone calls
he had been putting off.</i>

1301
01:32:28,450 --> 01:32:32,250
Listen, does your program
have an age limit?

1302
01:32:32,920 --> 01:32:35,430
<i>And he traveled to Ms Pascal's...</i>

1303
01:32:35,520 --> 01:32:38,960
<i>... where she made him meat loaf
and chocolate pudding...</i>

1304
01:32:38,960 --> 01:32:41,620
<i>... and the two watched old movies.</i>

1305
01:32:43,400 --> 01:32:45,230
<i>It was a nice enough evening.</i>

1306
01:32:45,230 --> 01:32:49,740
<i>And in any other circumstance
it would've seemed commonplace.</i>

1307
01:32:49,740 --> 01:32:53,340
<i>In fact, the only thing
that made this night significant...</i>

1308
01:32:53,340 --> 01:32:55,720
<i>... was the morning it preceded.</i>

1309
01:33:01,420 --> 01:33:03,710
I have to tell you something.

1310
01:33:03,920 --> 01:33:05,220
You do?

1311
01:33:06,120 --> 01:33:07,780
I do.

1312
01:33:08,590 --> 01:33:11,680
- Is it a secret?
- Sort of.

1313
01:33:11,890 --> 01:33:13,380
Tell me.

1314
01:33:15,100 --> 01:33:17,060
I adore you.

1315
01:33:20,270 --> 01:33:22,360
I adore you too.

1316
01:33:25,070 --> 01:33:28,510
- That it?
- No.

1317
01:33:29,710 --> 01:33:31,510
I have to tell you this.

1318
01:33:31,710 --> 01:33:34,310
I just want you to listen carefully.

1319
01:33:34,520 --> 01:33:36,070
Okay.

1320
01:33:37,420 --> 01:33:41,550
You can deduct the value
of all the food you give away...

1321
01:33:41,760 --> 01:33:44,330
...as a charitable contribution.
- Harold.

1322
01:33:44,490 --> 01:33:49,790
No, no, no. In fact it amounts to more
than what you're currently withholding.

1323
01:33:50,000 --> 01:33:52,240
And it doesn't break any tax laws.

1324
01:33:52,370 --> 01:33:56,560
Harold, the point
is to break the tax laws.

1325
01:33:56,770 --> 01:34:00,140
I wanna make the world
a better place too, Ana.

1326
01:34:01,110 --> 01:34:04,270
I think that means
keeping you out of jail.

1327
01:34:08,250 --> 01:34:09,740
Okay.

1328
01:34:10,420 --> 01:34:11,910
Okay?

1329
01:34:12,120 --> 01:34:13,590
- Yeah.
- Okay.

1330
01:34:13,790 --> 01:34:17,450
If you come over here...

1331
01:34:17,660 --> 01:34:21,860
...and talk a little more tax talk
in my ear.

1332
01:34:22,060 --> 01:34:24,400
Because I like it so much.

1333
01:35:47,350 --> 01:35:51,290
<i>Much had changed for Harold
over the past few weeks:</i>

1334
01:35:51,290 --> 01:35:53,450
<i>His attitude towards work.</i>

1335
01:35:53,450 --> 01:35:55,790
<i>His habitual counting.</i>

1336
01:35:56,090 --> 01:35:57,850
<i>His love life.</i>

1337
01:36:02,030 --> 01:36:05,600
<i>But of all the transmutations
Harold Crick had undergone...</i>

1338
01:36:05,600 --> 01:36:10,810
<i>... perhaps the most significant
was that today on his return to work...</i>

1339
01:36:10,810 --> 01:36:15,240
<i>... he was not late
for the 8:17 Kronecker bus.</i>

1340
01:36:17,910 --> 01:36:19,810
<i>What Harold had not understood...</i>

1341
01:36:19,810 --> 01:36:22,420
<i>... about that Wednesday
four weeks prior...</i>

1342
01:36:22,420 --> 01:36:25,390
<i>... was that the time he received from
his fellow commuter...</i>

1343
01:36:25,390 --> 01:36:29,320
<i>... was, in fact, three full minutes
later than the actual time...</i>

1344
01:36:29,320 --> 01:36:31,830
<i>... and, therefore, three full minutes
later...</i>

1345
01:36:31,830 --> 01:36:37,170
<i>... than the time to which his watch
and life had been previously set.</i>

1346
01:36:37,600 --> 01:36:39,960
<i>Not the worst of errors.</i>

1347
01:36:41,340 --> 01:36:44,870
<i>But if Harold had not set his watch
to the incorrect time...</i>

1348
01:36:44,870 --> 01:36:49,080
<i>... Harold would have again
barely caught the 8:17 Kronecker bus.</i>

1349
01:36:49,080 --> 01:36:51,410
<i>And he would not be approaching
the bus stop...</i>

1350
01:36:51,410 --> 01:36:54,820
<i>... precisely at 8:14
this particular Friday.</i>

1351
01:36:54,820 --> 01:36:56,280
Excuse me.

1352
01:37:00,320 --> 01:37:01,950
Harold?

1353
01:37:03,390 --> 01:37:05,700
<i>An otherwise ignorable fact...</i>

1354
01:37:06,060 --> 01:37:08,630
<i>... until the unthinkable occurred.</i>

1355
01:37:41,500 --> 01:37:43,760
Oh, my God. Oh, my God.

1356
01:37:43,970 --> 01:37:45,870
I need for everyone
to just stay seated.

1357
01:37:45,870 --> 01:37:47,390
Come on, son.

1358
01:37:52,540 --> 01:37:55,340
- What happened? I didn't see him.
- It was not your fault.

1359
01:37:55,340 --> 01:37:57,850
He was trying to help the boy.
Get your supervisor.

1360
01:37:57,850 --> 01:37:59,230
I don't believe this.

1361
01:37:59,250 --> 01:38:01,950
- It was all my fault, though.
- No, it wasn't.

1362
01:38:01,950 --> 01:38:03,140
Is he okay?

1363
01:38:03,350 --> 01:38:06,390
- It looks likes he's breathing.
- I don't think he's breathing.

1364
01:38:06,390 --> 01:38:07,680
Oh, my God.

1365
01:38:22,640 --> 01:38:23,800
Come in.

1366
01:38:27,510 --> 01:38:28,570
Excuse me.

1367
01:38:32,350 --> 01:38:34,580
Are you Professor Hilbert?

1368
01:38:36,280 --> 01:38:37,720
Yes.

1369
01:38:39,960 --> 01:38:42,450
Hi. I'm Karen Eiffel.

1370
01:38:43,260 --> 01:38:47,660
I believe we have
a mutual acquaintance.

1371
01:38:49,130 --> 01:38:51,330
Please, sit down.

1372
01:38:52,270 --> 01:38:54,790
No, I just came by to...

1373
01:38:55,870 --> 01:38:57,240
Here.

1374
01:39:00,610 --> 01:39:03,480
- Is that it?
- Yes.

1375
01:39:04,350 --> 01:39:06,040
Have you read it?

1376
01:39:07,680 --> 01:39:09,380
Is that all right?

1377
01:39:12,890 --> 01:39:14,410
Yes.

1378
01:39:16,960 --> 01:39:21,900
I think, perhaps, you may be
interested in the new ending.

1379
01:39:34,410 --> 01:39:36,270
Good afternoon.

1380
01:39:37,210 --> 01:39:38,940
Oh, hi.

1381
01:39:39,580 --> 01:39:41,880
It's a pretty brave thing you did.

1382
01:39:44,950 --> 01:39:48,060
Stepping in front of that bus
was pretty brave.

1383
01:39:49,590 --> 01:39:52,250
Kind of stupid, but pretty brave.

1384
01:39:52,460 --> 01:39:54,190
Oh, yeah.

1385
01:39:55,130 --> 01:39:56,760
Is that boy okay?

1386
01:39:56,970 --> 01:39:59,340
He's just fine. Scratched up is all.

1387
01:39:59,400 --> 01:40:01,030
Oh, good.

1388
01:40:03,510 --> 01:40:05,030
Am I okay?

1389
01:40:05,970 --> 01:40:07,840
Well, you're not dead.

1390
01:40:08,040 --> 01:40:11,050
On the other hand, it looks like
you cracked your head...

1391
01:40:11,050 --> 01:40:13,450
...you broke three bones
in your leg and foot...

1392
01:40:13,450 --> 01:40:16,350
...you suffered four broken ribs,
fractured your left arm...

1393
01:40:16,350 --> 01:40:20,460
...and severed an artery in your right,
which should've killed you in minutes.

1394
01:40:20,460 --> 01:40:21,650
But amazingly...

1395
01:40:21,860 --> 01:40:24,790
...a shard of metal from your watch
obstructed the artery...

1396
01:40:24,790 --> 01:40:27,930
...keeping the blood loss
low enough to keep you alive...

1397
01:40:27,930 --> 01:40:29,400
...which is pretty cool.

1398
01:40:30,730 --> 01:40:33,110
Yeah.
So with some physical therapy...

1399
01:40:33,200 --> 01:40:35,970
...a few months of rest,
you should be fine.

1400
01:40:36,270 --> 01:40:39,610
Well, sort of. We weren't able
to remove the shard of watch...

1401
01:40:39,610 --> 01:40:42,710
...from your arm without risking
severe arterial damage.

1402
01:40:42,710 --> 01:40:45,210
You'll be okay.
You'll just have a piece of watch...

1403
01:40:45,210 --> 01:40:48,120
...embedded in your arm
the rest of your life.

1404
01:40:48,120 --> 01:40:50,950
You're very lucky to be alive,
Mr Crick.

1405
01:40:51,890 --> 01:40:52,850
Yeah.

1406
01:40:57,090 --> 01:41:00,460
- Dr Mercator, Mr Crick has a visitor.
- Sure.

1407
01:41:01,500 --> 01:41:05,020
- My God, Harold.
- Hey.

1408
01:41:07,740 --> 01:41:10,500
- I'm okay. It's all right.
- Harold.

1409
01:41:10,710 --> 01:41:12,200
I'm fine.

1410
01:41:12,410 --> 01:41:15,000
Harold, you're not fine.

1411
01:41:15,210 --> 01:41:18,610
Look at you. You're severely injured.

1412
01:41:18,810 --> 01:41:21,780
- No, I'm fine.
- What...? What happened?

1413
01:41:22,950 --> 01:41:24,790
I stepped in front of a bus.

1414
01:41:24,790 --> 01:41:27,580
What? Why?

1415
01:41:27,790 --> 01:41:31,420
There was a boy.
I had to push him out of the way.

1416
01:41:31,630 --> 01:41:33,690
What?

1417
01:41:34,600 --> 01:41:37,830
I had to keep this boy from getting hit.

1418
01:41:41,240 --> 01:41:44,600
You stepped in front of a bus
to save a little boy?

1419
01:41:45,240 --> 01:41:47,330
I didn't have a choice.

1420
01:41:47,540 --> 01:41:49,170
I had to.

1421
01:42:03,630 --> 01:42:06,720
It's... It's okay.

1422
01:42:08,030 --> 01:42:10,730
- It's not great.
- No.

1423
01:42:10,930 --> 01:42:13,370
It's okay. It's not bad.

1424
01:42:13,800 --> 01:42:17,340
It's not the most amazing piece
of English literature in several years...

1425
01:42:17,340 --> 01:42:19,670
...but it's okay.

1426
01:42:21,740 --> 01:42:22,710
You know...

1427
01:42:25,180 --> 01:42:27,480
...I think I'm fine with "okay. "

1428
01:42:27,680 --> 01:42:30,420
It doesn't make sense
with the rest of the book though.

1429
01:42:30,420 --> 01:42:33,010
No, not yet. I'll rewrite the rest.

1430
01:42:33,220 --> 01:42:35,760
My assistant said
she'd go back to the publisher...

1431
01:42:35,760 --> 01:42:38,280
...and request more time.
- Why?

1432
01:42:38,730 --> 01:42:40,600
Don't know. It's awfully sweet though.

1433
01:42:40,600 --> 01:42:43,060
No, why did you change the book?

1434
01:42:45,500 --> 01:42:47,020
Lots of reasons.

1435
01:42:47,240 --> 01:42:49,970
I realized I just couldn't do it.

1436
01:42:51,270 --> 01:42:53,240
Because he's real?

1437
01:42:53,780 --> 01:42:56,540
Because it's a book about a man...

1438
01:42:56,750 --> 01:42:59,950
...who doesn't know he's about to die
and then dies.

1439
01:42:59,950 --> 01:43:03,840
But if the man does know
he's going to die and dies anyway...

1440
01:43:03,850 --> 01:43:07,020
...dies willingly,
knowing he could stop it, then...

1441
01:43:08,120 --> 01:43:12,120
I mean, isn't that the type of man
you want to keep alive?

1442
01:43:14,460 --> 01:43:17,500
<i>As Harold took a bite
of Bavarian sugar cookie...</i>

1443
01:43:17,500 --> 01:43:22,050
<i>... he finally felt as if everything
was going to be okay.</i>

1444
01:43:22,500 --> 01:43:26,270
<i>Sometimes, when we lose ourselves
in fear and despair...</i>

1445
01:43:26,270 --> 01:43:28,670
<i>... in routine and constancy...</i>

1446
01:43:29,780 --> 01:43:32,150
<i>... in hopelessness and tragedy...</i>

1447
01:43:32,550 --> 01:43:36,440
<i>... we can thank God
for Bavarian sugar cookies.</i>

1448
01:43:36,850 --> 01:43:39,790
<i>And fortunately,
when there aren't any cookies...</i>

1449
01:43:39,790 --> 01:43:44,800
<i>... we can still find reassurance
in a familiar hand on our skin...</i>

1450
01:43:45,860 --> 01:43:48,300
<i>... or a kind and loving gesture...</i>

1451
01:43:51,670 --> 01:43:53,910
<i>... or a subtle encouragement...</i>

1452
01:43:57,440 --> 01:43:59,770
<i>... or a loving embrace...</i>

1453
01:44:02,040 --> 01:44:04,880
<i>... or an offer of comfort.</i>

1454
01:44:05,650 --> 01:44:09,380
<i>Not to mention hospital gurneys...</i>

1455
01:44:11,350 --> 01:44:13,480
<i>... and nose plugs...</i>

1456
01:44:20,200 --> 01:44:22,560
<i>... and uneaten Danish...</i>

1457
01:44:24,670 --> 01:44:26,790
<i>... and soft-spoken secrets...</i>

1458
01:44:30,710 --> 01:44:33,540
<i>... and Fender Stratocasters...</i>

1459
01:44:34,210 --> 01:44:38,870
<i>... and maybe the occasional piece
of fiction.</i>

1460
01:44:39,980 --> 01:44:42,480
<i>And we must remember
that all these things...</i>

1461
01:44:42,480 --> 01:44:44,850
<i>... the nuances, the anomalies,
the subtleties...</i>

1462
01:44:44,850 --> 01:44:47,120
<i>... which we assume
only accessorize our days...</i>

1463
01:44:47,120 --> 01:44:51,680
<i>... are, in fact, here for a much larger
and nobler cause:</i>

1464
01:44:51,760 --> 01:44:54,960
<i>They are here to save our lives.</i>

1465
01:44:55,600 --> 01:44:58,190
<i>I know the idea seems strange.</i>

1466
01:44:58,400 --> 01:45:02,690
<i>But I also know that it
just so happens to be true.</i>

1467
01:45:03,010 --> 01:45:04,440
<i>And so it was:</i>

1468
01:45:04,640 --> 01:45:07,210
<i>A wristwatch saved Harold Crick.</i>

